Generates the shell fragment that runs `ctx-verify` and `ctx-context .` inside the cage before launching `claude`, captures their combined output into `$PREFLIGHT`, and appends both that output and the cage rules doctrine to `$SYSTEM_PROMPT_FILE` (which `claude` receives via `--append-system-prompt-file`). Tool failures don't halt the run; errors are logged inline and preflight serves open.

`probe(label, cmd)` wraps a single tool invocation in shell code that captures output, exit status, and prints a NOTE if nonzero. `snippet()` assembles two probes (`ctx-verify`, `ctx-context .`) with a newline between them, echoes the result to stdout, then concatenates `CAGE_RULES_PATH` and `$PREFLIGHT` into a temp file assigned to `$SYSTEM_PROMPT_FILE`.

`claude_invocation(headless)` returns the exact `exec` line passed to the shell: for headless (Task mode) it runs `claude -p --dangerously-skip-permissions --append-system-prompt-file "$SYSTEM_PROMPT_FILE" "$CTX_TASK_BRIEF"`; for interactive it wraps with `setsid --ctty --wait` to give `claude` a controlling PTY in its namespace (absence causes Node readline to busy-spin at 100% CPU). The `--append-system-prompt-file` path is the temp file created by `snippet()`, so both functions' outputs must coordinate.